512 bytes copied from disk by BIOS
Stack: undefined -- bootloader must set it
WARNING: Stage 1 Must Fit in 512 Bytes

IBM PC gated A20 via keyboard controller
Without A20: kernel at 0x100000 is unreachable
Stage 2 has ~7680 bytes to work with
Kernel lives above 1MB -- clear of BIOS data
Must have A20 enabled to reach 0x100000
Step 4b: GDT Layout (5 entries x 8 bytes = 40 bytes)
[0x00] Null descriptor -- required by CPU spec
[0x08] Kernel code DPL=0 base=0 lim=4GB access=0x9A
[0x10] Kernel data DPL=0 base=0 lim=4GB access=0x92
[0x18] User code DPL=3 base=0 lim=4GB access=0xFA
[0x20] User data DPL=3 base=0 lim=4GB access=0xF2
CPU now knows GDT location and size
NOT yet using GDT -- still in real mode
Why: IVT at 0x0000 is real-mode only.
If timer fires (IRQ0 -> vec 8 = double fault!)
CPU reads IVT as gate descriptors -> triple fault.
No interrupt must fire between cli and sti
CPU is now in Protected Mode.
BUT: CS still has old real-mode value!
Pipeline may have prefetched real-mode instrs.
This far jump does TWO critical things:
CPU looks up GDT[1]: base=0, lim=4GB, DPL=0
CPU restarts fetch under protected-mode rules
This is the point of no return.
mov ax, 0x10 ; kernel data selector = GDT[2]
mov ds, ax ; DS -> kernel data segment
mov ss, ax ; SS -> kernel data segment
Critical: Until these loads, DS/ES/SS contain
selectors -> likely null -> GPF on first mem access
CS was loaded by the far jump.
C guarantees global int x; starts at zero.
ELF BSS occupies NO disk space -- linker records only size.
YOUR kernel must zero it (no OS to do it for you).
; Linker exports these symbols from kernel.ld:
rep stosd ; store 4 bytes per iter
; Note: if BSS not mult of 4, use rep stosb
Skip this -> global int arr[1000] has garbage.
Bug manifests far from cause (used much later).
If kernel linked at wrong address:
all function calls, global accesses -> wrong addrs
; Stack is set, BSS is zeroed
call kmain ; Far call to C entry point
VGA buffer at phys 0xB8000 -- MMIO, no cache
Serial at I/O port 0x3F8 -- port-mapped I/O
